        "\n",
        "## Definition\n",
        "\n",
        "**Multicollinearity** occurs when two or more predictor variables in a regression model are highly correlated.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Variance Inflation Factor (VIF)\n",
        "\n",
        "$$VIF_k = \\frac{1}{1 - R_k^2}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Where $R_k^2$ is from regressing predictor $X_k$ on all other predictors.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Interpretation Thresholds\n",
        "\n",
        "| VIF Value | Severity |\n",
        "|-----------|----------|\n",
        "| **VIF = 1** | No correlation with other predictors |\n",
        "| **1 < VIF < 5** | Moderate correlation (acceptable) |\n",
        "| **5 ≤ VIF < 10** | Problematic multicollinearity |\n",
        "| **VIF ≥ 10** | Severe multicollinearity |\n",
        "\n",
        "## Why Multicollinearity Matters in Volatility Modeling\n",
        "\n",
        "When predictors are highly correlated:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Unreliable coefficients** - Can't identify true risk factors\n",
        "2. **Unstable hedging ratios** - Estimates vary wildly with new data\n",
        "3. **Inflated standard errors** - Wrong statistical conclusions about significance\n",
        "4. **Wrong coefficient signs** - Direction of relationship may be incorrect\n",
        "5. **Poor out-of-sample performance** - Models don't generalize\n",
        "\n",
        "## Common Sources of Multicollinearity in Finance\n",
        "\n",
        "| Source | Example |\n",
        "|--------|---------|\n",
        "| **Moving averages** | SMA_5 and SMA_10 are naturally correlated |\n",
        "| **Lagged variables** | Returns at t-1 and t-2 are often correlated |\n",
        "| **Variance measures** | Realized volatility across different windows |\n",
